Lignum Vitae has long been a favorite wood of mine. It is the densest wood in the world.  It takes good detail but because it it so oily it has its challenges.

A fellow carver posted one the other day and got me digging through my wood bin to make this.
.
 Almost  done. 

The wood has a wonderful aroma.  Usually it attracts bees.
.
.
Will be available.

Phenolic Resin WIP

Phenolic resins were first made in 1872 when Adolph Baeyer reacted phenol with acetaldehyde.
 Bakelite phenoic resins were developed by Leo Baekeland beginning in 1907. Examples of phenolic resins are Bakelite, Novolac and Catalin. Phenolic resins are used for molded parts, as adhesives and as varnishes.
 Bakelite, a trademarked phenolic plastic, revolutionized the market for molded and laminated parts for use in electrical equipment. Phenolics are still very important industrial polymers.

Very pleased. Sanding this is just as crazy. I can't imagine doing this on an opaque material. I'm cheating and putting the lean over the image.  Also I can haol it up to the light and carve.  For some reason it works better with one eye closed.  I'll try to finish ths and don't think I'll try this again.  Mad respect to those who do this on gemstone.

I have a few woolly mammoth ivory skulls that have cracks in the material.  This is 10,000 year old, or older, material so cracks are not uncommon  I have stabilized the material to prevent  further cracks  but I just can't sell them as A grade. Some people would try to get full price, i just cant do that. This is one of them.  About 16mm tall
You can see the crack on the back.  It will still make a great pendant or bead or just a miniature for your shelf.  I have a few more to finish up and will offer them at half price or less. 

If you are interested let me know.
